Parliament rejects amendment liberating Tymoshenko
Ukraine’s parliament on Thursday rejected a proposal to repeal a section on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko was convicted.
The amendment, which would pave the way for the release of the imprisoned former prime minister, was rejected by MPs at the second reading of a proposal to ease penalties for economic crimes.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for concluding an allegedly unfavorable contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not final, the appeal of the convicted is to be heard by the court in December.
Tymoshenko described the verdict as political revenge of the regime, suspicion of court bias triggered a trial in the West.
The proposal to remove paragraph 365 from the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 MPs in the vote.
226 votes were needed to approve it.
