EU Ambassador Vicenov<0xC3><0xA1>:
Czechs have a reputation for being negative and Eurosceptic
"The Lisbon Treaty has seriously upset the balance between the various institutions."
"I didn't expect it to be such a hard war."
"It will take five, six years for the situation to settle down, calm down and for all players to get used to their new roles," Czech Ambassador to the European Union Milena Vicenov<0xC3><0xA1> began her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
To what extent she takes her motto "Clearly and openly about Europe" seriously, she already showed in the first part of the lecture, when she managed to describe the individual EU institutions and their relations in such a clear and understandable way that many lecturers from the Faculty of Law of the UK could envy her.
Vicen also praised the work of the new Permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first, there was criticism that he was indistinct, that he was a gray clerk, that he could not perform any role, and I must say that everyone was blown away, that the role was excellent."
"He is a person who can listen to twenty-seven Member States, communicates well with them and has a clear vision of where the European Union should go."
She then explained the new post of High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy as an answer to the question: "Who is the European Union? What phone number should I call?", i.e. as an important step towards unification and greater readability of EU policy towards countries such as China or India.
No one wants to ban mermaids.
Vicenov<0xC3><0xA1> also addressed the agenda that the European Council has lived, lives and will live in the near future.
She called the Czech Presidency a success.
The Czechs have dealt with the onset of the financial crisis, solved the gas crisis or organized a summit for the Eastern Partnership.
She then called the fall of the government at that time a great negative, which greatly damaged the Czech Republic.
The Czech representation in the EU is currently very busy.
In the words of the Ambassador, the "fact of frmol" was not only the Presidency, but also the subsequent financial crisis, which is still being resolved today.
In addition, the new seven-year budget of the Union has yet to be approved, which is becoming much more complicated due to the current economic situation.
Whether the budget will be slender and austere, which sectors will be preferred, which countries will be supported more and which less, all are on the agenda of the next negotiations.
The Ambassador also recalled her main slogans with which she came to Brussels: "On Europe intelligible".
"I really don't like ugly abbreviations, strange words, a lingerie that no one understands.
How can a citizen understand that curvy or round cucumbers are not really invented in Brussels, bananas of different sizes, or that someone really has to ban us cheeses?
He also wants to make better use of the EU environment and get more Czechs into European institutions.
A multi-speed Europe awaits us
According to the ambassador, Czechs have a reputation as eurosceptics and people who notice the negative rather than the positive aspects of things.
Moreover, she regrets the low representation of Czechs in European institutions.
According to her, many factors are to blame, for example, the modesty of our candidates, their inability to write motivational letters, but also low support from the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech Presidency, she also highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Four.
"Believe me, when a Pole and a Hungarian come to me and a Slovak approaches, the Frenchman next to me will say, 'Look, what are you meeting there, what about your Visegrad Four?' and he doesn't look excited about it at all."
In the future, the Union, according to Vicen<0xC3><0xA1>, is waiting mainly for new tough rules for the budgetary policies of the member states.
He sees the concept of a two-speed, if not multi-speed Europe as very real, rather than a new "European federation."
"We have countries in the eurozone and countries outside the eurozone."
"We have the Schengen area, we already have an institute of enhanced cooperation."
“For the first time, it was said that only countries that wanted to cooperate and those that didn’t want to stay away.”
"There will be more of these institutes and it will be a strong two-speed Europe," Vicenov<0xC3><0xA1> expects.
In this respect, it also appreciated the role of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in enforcing the principle that all topics having an impact on the whole of the Union should be discussed between all Member States, and not just between euro area countries.
Brand story:
IBM innovator begins second century of its existence
If someone were looking for a word that most accurately expresses IBM’s strategy, the closest one would probably be “longevity.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is a company perceived as very present, and yet it has been a hundred years since its foundation.
The foundation of this longevity was laid by the company’s first CEO, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already coined the slogan that many of the world’s problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
