IBM History: From Cheese Slicer to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a century ago, originally called Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was not adopted until 1924 – originally a brand used for the company’s branches in Canada and South America.
The basis for the later IBM was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They owned technologies such as the famous "pussy", that is, the clock recording the employee's arrival and departure.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired the supervisory board of the company.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, the head of a rival company, to help him manage the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of IBM - Watson's ideas are still built on an invincible corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started with the production and sale of all sorts of machines for business - from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four years that Watson led the company, the company doubled its turnover to $9 million and began a large-scale expansion of the company to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after almost forty years in the boss's chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Jr..
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence, developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM’s people and computers helped NASA fly into space—to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the famous man-to-moon flight.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "bake" that set the computer standard of the time, called IBM 5150, came to market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the production of computers to the Chinese company Lenovo, on the contrary, it bought the consulting part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to fully devote itself to consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the concept of Smarter Planet.
Its aim is the smart use of technologies in areas that have not yet been planned and the improvement of the situation, for example in transport or city administration.
IBM recently launched the “Smarter Commerce” platform to help traders manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history in the country.
It established its branch in the then Czechoslovakia already in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM Czech Republic, there is also a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern European Centre is headquartered in Prague and there is also a world-class voice recognition research team.
