How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies were selling, for the most part, only trips to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Thus, Czech tourists traveled on holiday to the sea to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in the Crimea by the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia was also available, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the travels of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand the queue overnight with a sleeping bag or to have "good friends" in the travel agency.
However, this was not the case.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (the Western currency) for the trip to the West.
By far, however, most often the Czechs spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs acquired and this custom survives to this day.
The journey of the Czechs has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible for us to travel to Croatia, currently the most popular one, until 1989, as it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the visa requirement for neighbouring Western European countries was abolished, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits, mainly to Austria’s Vienna or Germany.
For a long time the Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West, everyone wanted to look there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czechs slept in parks in tents, because our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of the travel of the Czechs at this time was driving their own food, cans, salami, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to buy the Western currency freely after many decades.
However, our standard of living and, with it, our average wages have risen, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have been preparing charter flights regularly since 1997, making air travel incredibly cheaper than in the past due to the possibility to negotiate volume discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs already had visa-free travel to almost all developed countries in the world, except the USA, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came in 2000, when, due to significant demand, the first direct charter flight to exotic destinations was made from the Czech Republic, to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters fly with Czech tourists every year to warm distant countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100 thousand Czechs every year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history they spent more than CZK 15,000 per person for one foreign holiday, including the cost of the place of residence.
