Smart Crows Are Spreading in Cities
In many places, field ravens are considered "problem birds": However, these highly intelligent animals can no longer be expelled from cities, experts say.
Some people like them, others would like to get rid of them quite quickly: Crows have been part of the image of the city for centuries, but in some villages complaints of pollution and noise caused by animals accumulate.
At the same time, there is not yet any means in sight against the "problem birds".
Field ravens can no longer be expelled from cities, experts said at the first symposium on crows in East Frisian Leer.
There, experts from all over the federal territory consulted on possible exits.
Looking for alternatives in cities
Conservationists also derived the problems of cities from the exodus of specially protected field ravens: The use of chemistry in agriculture is probably increasingly destroying traditional areas for life.
Persecution, growing development and felling of typical nesting trees make life difficult for birds.
The crows are protected.
Large colonies with more than 600 nesting pairs are located, among others, in Westphalia's Soest, in the northwest, among others, in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen and Leer.
There in 2005 a controversial project of mass killing crows in a rural district triggered negative headlines.
Critics have labeled catching animals in bird traps and slaughtering sticks as particularly brutal.
"Normal expulsion, fear, brings nothing," said the urbanist and landscape designer Werner Klöver of Leer.
The removal of nests by spraying water or cutting down trees often has undesirable consequences, environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg said.
"Animals are retreating, large colonies are splitting and dividing into other places."
Fear is conceivable only as an exception in hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them out."
Without the surrounding territory, the problem of cities cannot be solved, was the opinion of Mayor Wolfgang Kellner of Leer.
A combination of expelling animals from sensitive habitats and attracting them to settle elsewhere is conceivable.
The "information board instead of chainsaws" was promoted by the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens because of the completely different treatment of animals: "One custard in the face, in the end, we can best withstand self-confidence."
Mrs. Jürgens co-founded the Ascherberg Scientific Crow Trail in Schleswig-Holstein, on which information boards provide lessons about the life of a highly intelligent field raven.
In the meantime, the project has already been accepted by tourists.
Also on the criticism of the noise caused by birds, Mrs Jürgens had her own opinion: "This is about every volume of communication, they have a lot to say."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: field ravens not only use tools to achieve a treat, but even make their tools as a tool.
Researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested behavior on four field ravens as far as bird intelligence goes.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that the stones must cause the structure to collapse to get to the larvae of the pier.
