Massacre on a personal level
Peter Englund’s emotionally powerful new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a long list of characters that will make your head spin.
One piece of advice on how to behave at this point: Carefully tear this page out and make a bookmark of it.
You will be very familiar with all the people in Mr. Englund's novel, and this list will serve as a navigation - as a kind of beacon - at times when, like the men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in various situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also a new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book we are discussing here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite appropriately, as an "anti-historical work".
It contains several very well-known names, important contracts or famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists, as well as discussions about tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, as rather a "book about what it was like". It is mainly about "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Sorrow" combines the war experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose their limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives flicker like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the tangle of fate, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book differs from classic historical novels.
It rewrites the notion that the First World War was all about the horrific trenches fighting on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skilfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with the fact that bee nests fall on them, they have to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids or face the presence of tse-tse flies.
This is a very touching reading almost from the beginning.
War devours the lives of humans like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina, which smells like gunpowder.
When gunfire begins to ring in the distance and you are the woman who is home with your children, will you run away or stay?
Who's actually coming?
Almost no one understands what is going on, not even why the whole war has been unleashed.
"The vacuum of lack of facts," said Mr. Englund, "was filled with conjectures, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmorough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are generally taken from biographies, letters and other materials already published.
The descriptions of their lives may sound frightening and engaging, but thanks to the inclusion of small moments and details, they are absolutely vivid and believable.
Many of them talk about suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: "Substitutes, everywhere just substitutes."
"Coffee substitute, aluminum imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "meat made from pressed rice cooked in sheepskin fat (and supplemented with fake bone from wood), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato peels, shoes with wooden soles".
He mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
An American finds his inner instincts for savagery and brutality, and then he declares about the war: "Finally, you will understand that this is human nature. Not sitting in comfortable chairs with a cigarette and whiskey, an evening newspaper or a good book, pretending that this mask of yours represents civilization and that there is no starch in it."
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he is most likely to die soon, and no one will even notice, let alone mourn.
“When one finally accepts that one is sacrificing oneself, one would at least expect that to happen in front of a grateful audience,” he writes.
Instead, he feels like a “convict who is secretly hanged.”
Other remarks concern the departure of old Europe and the onset of new horrors.
“Conflict has increasingly become an economic competition and a competitive struggle,” writes Mr. Englund, “a war between factories.”
He captures what he calls “the new kind of beast of the coming century: an eloquent and ideologically sworn mass murderer in a custom-made dress who carries out his bloodshed without getting up from the table.”
People behave completely unexpectedly, meanness alternates with heroism.
Mr. Englund also describes soldiers who deliberately tried to catch a sexual illness from prostitutes in order to avoid serving on the front lines.
"The most grotesque example of this behavior was the trade in gonococcal pus, which the soldiers were buying and smashing their genitals with in the hope of ending up in the hospital," he wrote.
"The most desperate rubbed it in their eyes, which often blinded them for the rest of their lives."
In this translation from Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund’s prose is fast-paced, but not spectacular, which fits perfectly with his human theme.
In dozens of small outputs, it captures the way in which war has unleashed utterly uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred.
People are beginning to wonder why their leaders are forcing them to fight.
The best books on World War I mostly worked with hints rather than complex narratives, such as Paul Fussell's "World War I and Modern Memories" or novels such as "On the Western Front Quiet" by Erich Maria Remarque.
Mr. Englund prefers an unconventional concept.
His book has the most overwhelming endings that are unparalleled in popular scientific literature.
But I will not tell you.
However, you will feel as if the author suddenly jumped out of the book, ripped the page out of your hero list and set it on fire.
