The union of auxiliary workers will sue the city for dismissal
Unions representing hundreds of school helpers who lost their jobs last month are planning to sue the city on Wednesday, saying the layoffs were unnecessary and moreover discriminatory, due to the disproportionate impact on schools attended by poor students.
The trial is probably the last option left to the District Council 37 unions in their attempt to reverse the dismissal decision.
On 7 October, six hundred and seventy-two school assistants, parental coordinators and other employees, who were among the city's worst-paid employees, lost their jobs. Their dismissal was described by union leaders as a retribution of the city for not allowing it access to a labor-controlled health care fund last spring, with which the city wanted to glue into the city.
City officials categorically denied the accusation.
At a town council meeting last month, Education Minister Dennis M. Walcott said the layoffs were part of a budget approved in June.
One member of the council immediately countered by saying that the budget did not specifically mention the dismissal of auxiliary workers.
Representatives of the district of District Council 37 announced that they had already filled out the necessary documents and warned the Ministry of Education that they would sue him. On Wednesday, they will convene a press conference, where they will formally announce the lawsuit at the Supreme State Court in Manhattan.
The defendants in the trial will be Mr Walcott and the Ministry of Education, while the plaintiffs will be eight redundant workers, all of whom are African-American or Hispanic, as well as most of the other assistants who have lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, a spokeswoman for the city’s legal department, said the city had not yet seen the lawsuit and would therefore not comment on the individual charges.
According to a draft complaint obtained by the New York Times, unions focused on the number of people released in poor parts of the city to back up their claims of unfair behavior, arguing that poor schools have lost more assistants because they have long been denied sufficient funding.
They point out that while there were no redundancies in the schools in Staten Island and only minimal redundancies in the Upper East Side, in Brooklyn, 17 school assistants were lost in District 23 in Brownsville, and 46 assistants in District 8 and 9 in the South Bronx.
He recalls that at Public School 36 in Harlem, five out of eight assistants lost their jobs, even though it is a school where 68 percent of students live in poverty.
The budget of Public School 36 was cut by 3.26 percent this year, and the school also lost money when the city changed the way bonus funds were calculated for every poor student enrolled.
The unions argue, among other things, that high school principals may have been confused by the way in which the document authorizing the dismissal of parental coordinators was written.
In the document, the word "excess" was used to describe the action, i.e. to cancel the position, although this word is much more often used to describe the transfer of the teacher from the school payroll to the database of available employees whose salary is paid by the central authority.
"Sixty-six parental coordinators have been released," the complaint draft says, "and not just moved to the database as available staff."
The mission is over, Congress is ready to accept the agreement on the situation in Libya
Finally, Republicans and Democrats in Congress seem to agree on something about the uprising in Libya.
But before that, the revolution had to succeed, long-ruling dictator Muammar Gaddafi had to be captured and killed, and the involvement of U.S. troops ended.
On Tuesday, the Senate Foreign Relations Commission will decide on a statement backed by President John Kerry (Mass.) along with Senators John McCain (Ariz.) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Conn.), in which it should congratulate Libyans on their successful uprising and thank U.S. troops for their "courage".
"With this statement, we want to appreciate the courage of the Libyan people who have started rebuilding their country," Kerry said.
"Both sides of the political spectrum would like to express their support for their democratic efforts."
The above-mentioned sentences may seem innocent, but no debate concerning Libya has hitherto been easy.
Over the summer, lawmakers from both sides have repeatedly argued with each other and the White House over the wording of a series of statements to approve or reject the United States’ military role in NATO’s mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain presented a resolution authorizing the limited use of U.S. forces in Libya.
The proposal was rejected in the House because of the differing views of both political parties, so it was never even voted on in the Senate.
However, on the same day that the motion was rejected in the House, the House also rejected measures that would stop funding US operations in Libya.
This put the U.S. mission in Libya literally in legislative purgatory — Congress criticized President Obama’s handling of the mission, but it obviously didn’t irritate its members enough to stop supporting him in his actions.
The hesitation of the Congress was finally preceded by other events.
The rebels captured Tripoli in August and Gaddafi was killed on October 20.
The NATO mission officially ended on October 31.
The Senate may be ready to act.
In its statement, the International Relations Commission “congratulates the people of Libya for their immense courage and admirable tenacity in their efforts to liberate their people” and “praises the men and women of the United States Armed Forces and their allies who have taken part in the operation to protect the Libyan population, for their extraordinary courage and professionalism.”
The statement also "reaffirms the national interest of the United States in a successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya."
Will the new proposal get the full support of the Commission on International Relations, or will the legislators be re-divided into two halves, as was the case when the June proposal was approved?
The latest version was opposed by Senator Richard G. Lugar (Indian), the main representative of the Republican Party in the commission.
Lugar's spokesman said on Monday that he had not yet seen the final version of the new proposal.
The House will vote this week on a constitutional amendment that would require a balanced budget, which should be the highest legislative priority for almost all Republicans and Democrats in Congress.
This measure, promoted by Bob Goodlatt (Va.), will be the first amendment to the Constitution on a budget or other topic to be voted on by the entire House or Senate.
For the time being, the other legislators, despite considerable efforts, have not yet succeeded in pushing their proposals to the vote itself.
Goodlatt's proposal is just one of 68 amendments to the constitution that were introduced in Congress and touched on a wide range of different topics.
Some of them were the same - the same proposal submitted to the House and the Senate - and others are just minor variations of others.
Only in the House can you find at least 15 versions of a balanced budget amendment and another handful that would like to "regulate federal spending".
Some of the proposals are identical, but their proponents - especially novice Republicans who want to improve their reputation - can boast of their "authority".
The decree on the regulation of the budget, which was approved in August, required both the House and the Senate to vote on the amendment on the balanced budget.
In March, 58 senators voted in favor of a non-binding statement in support of the creation of such an amendment.
In addition to the budget, several members want to discuss limiting the number of periods during which members of Congress can serve, while José E. Serrano (N.Y.) wants to increase the number of periods that can be president.
Deputy Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Ill.) offered a variety of supplements that would, among other things, guarantee the right to quality education and medical care.
An amendment banning same-sex marriage and an amendment banning the burning of the national flag remains a permanent proposal.
Some lawmakers also want to allow federal laws to be repealed if two-thirds of states oppose them.
Although members of Congress appear to be very active in drafting various amendments, they do not differ significantly from the average in comparison with previous years.
In the 111th Congress they offered 77 amendments, while in the 100th Congress there were 66.
Their activity even pales compared to the early 1990s, when, according to statistics from the Senate Library, members offered more than 150 allowances every two years.
However, they were not much more successful than current politicians.
The last amendment that was added - the 27th Amendment - was ratified in 1992, but in fact it was proposed by Congress in 1789.
