Military units meet with compassion rather than respect.
The event was a gala night on Wall Street that brought in millions of dollars for war veterans in New York who have no roof over their heads.
Kid Rock sang a ballad of helplessness, frustration, and loss.
Hundreds of soldiers, sailors, airmen, and marines gathered around him.
The ceremonially dressed crowd rose and applauded enthusiastically.
“The men and women serving in the military were considered heroes,” said David Saltzman, who organized the Spring Benefit.
In addition to Admiral Mike Mullen, who saw the role of the military units somewhat differently, the chairman of the Chiefs of Staff Committee also attended the ceremony.
"They were all presented as orphans," the officer wrote in an e-mail.
I'm sure the organizers meant it well.
I know you do.
But what I saw wasn't respect, it was regret.
So completely opposite impressions only illustrate the difficult relationship between the military and the often measured, sometimes glorifying American public.
The army is indiscriminately included in the praise of its victims.
But this praise is worth something, say the soldiers.
Increasingly, the public acts as if they feel sorry for the individual in uniform.
"We are not victims at all," said Brigadier General Sean B. MacFarland, who commanded troops in Iraq and will soon leave Afghanistan.
"But it seems that the only way some can support us is to put us in the role of unhappy souls."
This topic is very sensitive for military commanders who do not want to look ungrateful or spoil their relations with the public they serve.
They also realize that the anger that the troops returning from Vietnam had to face was much worse.
As a result, most words of regret are spoken in silence and in private among war veterans.
When the two sons of retired colonel Mark Cancian returned from combat operations, where they served as Marines, their father warned them that their service would be viewed from two angles.
From the point of view of some, they will feel respect and wonder, as they defeated the enemy insurgents and visited exotic places.
But others will wonder if “there is an evil, violent veteran hiding under the surface,” said Cancian, who took part in the fighting in Iraq and took a seat in Washington’s government on his return.
He claimed that when he was looking for a job, some people who interviewed him were inconspicuously suggesting that he could withstand the stress of working in Washington so soon after returning from combat.
"When you talk about your service, you have to expect negative reactions," Cancian told his sons.
The military’s concern stems in part from America’s indifference to war.
Success on the battlefield is rarely recognized in a country that has little knowledge of its own army and finds little self-interest in the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
“As a nation, we no longer value military heroism as we did during World War II,” said Lt. Gen. David Barno, who commanded U.S. troops in Afghanistan.
Instead, recognition by politicians and the public focuses mainly on the suffering of men in arms.
Soldiers are awarded for the number of actions they have suffered, the number of friends they have lost, or the extent of their injuries.
The military is facing increasing pressure to crack down on rape.
This week, it will be decided whether to start a trial of 28 women and men against the army for alleged inaction in the case of rape.
If not, they are ready to file a lawsuit against hundreds of other applicants.
The first-class soldier, Elizabeth Lyman, was 25 years old on the night she was allegedly raped by her military colleague and was 11 weeks pregnant.
It happened in October 2008 and she was heading to the barracks at Miramar Air Force Base north of San Diego. After dinner with a friend, she bumped into her male colleague carrying a box of 12 beers.
He asked her if she could join him, if they could have a drink in her room.
"I've got a warning light in my head," Lyman said.
But the native Texan completely ignored her objections.
I thought, No, he's 19.
"He's from Texas," she said.
"I wish I'd listened to my instincts."
She claims that just minutes after they entered her room, the man walked over to her, threw her on the bed and raped her.
This week, November 18, Lyman and 27 other existing or former members of the military will await a verdict of a hearing that could have a historic impact. This will take place in Arlington, Virginia, and it will be about whether the charges against former Defense Secretary Robert Gates and his predecessor, Donald Rumsfeld, will be brought before the court.
The indictment alleges that Gates and Rumsfeld failed to combat the spread of rape in the military, which is contrary to the constitutional rights of soldiers.
The indictment was filed in February by Washington lawyer Susan Burke, and the plaintiffs had 17 members at the time, but over the following months their number grew to 28 to 25 women and three men, all of whom claimed to have been raped or otherwise sexually assaulted by their colleagues in the military and that the army failed to investigate, punish and prosecute any charges.
Burke says she's going after the highest-ranking army commanders because the problem starts with them.
“The military is a directive system,” he says.
"Who are the people who are in a position to prevent efforts to put in place measures against such acts?
Burke also says she has contacted at least 400 other survivors since February, many of whom could become part of other lawsuits filed in the future.
Her strategy: Rather than grouping all the accusations into this case — stacking all the eggs in one basket, she says — she’ll file lawsuits in multiple different cases, if necessary, so that the pressure doesn’t ease.
The Defense Department’s defense team is led by U.S. Attorney Neil MacBride, who together with his associates filed a motion to dismiss the case.
The court documents obtained by Newsweek discuss in detail the strategy of the defense - in principle, the fact that current or former soldiers can not sue the army for injuries suffered as members of the armed forces.
According to a 1950 Supreme Court order called Feres Doctrine, the federal government is not responsible for injuries suffered by soldiers in active service.
"The alleged injuries relate to the military service of the plaintiffs," the document reads.
The Department of Defense declined to comment on the matter.
However, things have changed since the 1950s.
Although women are still not officially allowed to serve in combat, it is only a matter of wordplay: in modern wars it is difficult to find a clearly defined front line.
In the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, teams of female soldiers have played an increasingly prominent role, especially in the area of communication with civilian women in the war zone.
The result: between these wars, 150 female soldiers fell - two-thirds of them directly in combat.
The time has come for modernization in the military, Burke explains.
She's not alone in her fight, except for three other attorneys.
At Yale Law School, visitors to a veterans’ seminar on legal services are preparing a lawsuit against four major military academies for allegedly developing an atmosphere fostering hatred for women.
Independently, a non-profit organization of U.S. veterans is gathering evidence for its lawsuit against the military. This lawsuit focuses on the diagnosis of "personality disorders" that were allegedly found in rape victims so that the army had an excuse to release them - according to activists such as Anu Network Ahagwati's rights include
In December, her group filed a lawsuit against a state organization for dealing with veterans, accusing her of discriminatory practices that should have taken place when processing requests for help from people who claimed to have been sexually assaulted in the service.
Nine separate motions were presented to Congress by a group of senators and lawmakers from both political parties, proposing a number of corrective measures.
According to the Department of Defense’s Office for the Prevention and Management of Sexual Violence, 3,158 sexual assaults were reported in 2010.
However, this type of attack remains largely unreported, and according to Pentagon estimates, the number corresponds to about 13.5 percent of the estimated 19,000 incidents that occurred in that year.
The March report also discusses the degree of criminal prosecution of suspects: In 2010, 20 percent of cases reported in the military were brought to justice – half of the civilian justice system.
Prosecutors in the case of Deputy Burke describe the attacks as only the first of a number of traumas.
First-class soldier Lyman, for example, reported the alleged rape to military police less than an hour after it was due to take place.
During the night, she was asked to repeat details of her rape eleven times to various police officers, doctors and commanders.
She underwent all the examinations necessary to determine the rape, and the blood of the assailant was found in her bed - from the wound she had done on his arm.
Six months later, in April 2009, Lyman underwent a court hearing during which she was asked questions about whether she had made love to her boyfriend on the day of the attack.
Six people were summoned to testify as witnesses to the rumor in favour of the alleged perpetrator, who was eventually acquitted.
"I remember the day the verdict was handed down," Lyman said.
