In January 2010, she was discharged from the army without honor and therefore without the right to service.
Whether the case of Lyman and the other prosecutors moves to the next stage or not, it’s a long run, says John Turley, a law professor at George Washington Law University.
However, he notes, "From my point of view, they should be able to move on to the next stages of the discussion."
But between them and the verdict stands the doctrine, which has been criticized since the first moment it saw the light of the world.
I myself am a lifelong critic of the Feres Doctrine.
The military is decades behind because their responsibilities do not allow for the same level of motivational incentives and deterrents.
