After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
“We realized that getting them isn’t really that hard,” said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by a British research team on European digital populism.
Facebook’s stock of personal information is so vast, Bartlett says, that scientists just needed to simply use the ads on the site to pinpoint the demographics they were looking for—something marketing professionals have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million right-wing fans across Europe, focusing on them and sending them ads, but instead of inviting them to the newly formed group or offering them some dietary products, they were asked to fill out a questionnaire on their own regarding the level of violence and their relationship to education.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries – without ever having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are generally young men who are stoked by rising immigration rates.
But on the other hand, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen.”
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and policy researchers use this site to study everything from health issues to social trends hiding state updates, wall posts, and “Like” buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. On average, each of them will provide three different data per day, which makes this social network literally an "information supernova", which is behind the development of many new research. The number of academic works in whose name the word Facebook occurs has increased compared to five years ago to almost 800%.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
“It used to be that when you wanted to do a survey among people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
"You'd have to get to a side where they'd never let you go," Bartlett says.
“Facebook is breaking up all of this – you’re just going straight to them.”
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a social health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, a research team found that university students who discussed their drinking outcomes on Facebook were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that students' peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
"The problem cannot be solved unless you can diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moreno's Washington Post and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle.
"We have found a way to identify endangered children that we would otherwise not have had a chance to discover."
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The site’s information team has compiled statistics on the relationship between the relationship status and Valentine’s Day, the 2010 voter turnout and the nation’s satisfaction coefficient (mainly using the information they had access to – advocates of internet freedom have long argued that the site should make its information treasure accessible to research and others).
But Facebook users know that the site is following them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you need to provide the site with your personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don’t even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data offline, but online data is accessible to everyone.
“I don’t think most users even thought that scientists could look at their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using the public Facebook walls of his students.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it that the information was only between them and their friends."
It is also necessary to consider the question of methodology.
Even when researching offline, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
It is not possible to verify on Facebook how much of the information on the profile and posts on the wall are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn said.
That’s why Selwin, who has spent many years researching new technologies, thinks that pencil and notebook continue to be the best tool that can be used in research.
“When you go out into the real world and talk to real people, it’s something that can’t be replaced,” she says.
“Social research should be about society and social activities – and a hell of a lot of social activities are still taking place offline.”
