Studies show that in one day you lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Assume that many of them are merciful lies.
Another study found that strangers lied three times during the first ten minutes of their first encounter.
Determining lies, or "recognition of lies", is a necessary skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or work reasons.
But it's not a social game that's similar to, say, Sharada, when one shouts, "I got you." Deception recognition is a serious branch of science working with scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities during detailed research projects, especially in the field of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been refuted.
The liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're squirming, they're cocktailing, they're blushing, or they're sewing.
However, do not assume that it is somehow difficult to spot the liars and expose them.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from the sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are created and their timing.
I have spent several years collecting scientific knowledge from a vast and growing industry related to the recognition of lies, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and can help you a lot in today's complex world - especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, conducting interviews, negotiating or leading people.
Good liars are able to read well in others, let them relax in vigilance, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more lies "focused on others" - mostly to protect one's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than single people (but the lies they say are usually "relentless").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
This is called “initial observation.”
Thanks to him, he will have a later find out what to compare with.
Notice the body posture of the subject, his laughter, work with the voice.
You should know if someone is routinely tapping their feet so you don’t unduly accuse them of lying just because they start tapping their feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and non-verbal behavior.
But consider it only as a warning signal, not as proof of a lie.
People telling lies can stop moving their upper half of the body when trying to remember their fictional story, they can turn their shoe tips to the door, lean toward the exit, significantly change their posture, or show "relief after the end of the conversation" - exaggerated relief breathing and changing position when it is difficult to confess them.
Interviewers often give a false signal that the interview is over, just to see what the relief will look like after it is over.
Notice the subject’s language as well.
The famous story is about how Scott Peterson once renounced and used the past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which sparked a nationwide search for her body.
Deceiving individuals can also express themselves in a measured way: “I had no sexual relationship with that lady... Miss Lewinsky” or repeat the difficult question all over again.
The most common verbal signs are only very minor.
Someone can use a lot of "softening language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... from what I know... to the best of my knowledge."
In such a response, we do not know much of the facts, and often this is another warning signal.
There is no magic by which every lie can be revealed, but it is possible to acquire the skills by which a lie can be traced.
With the help of these skills, a person will have a better chance of not hitting a liar and a cheater in his personal and professional life.
