Climate change slows down the economy
During the first year of the government of Maria L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdez, unemployment and unreliability increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment and the economy declined with it.
The year 2011 will be recorded in the economic history of Sinaloa. This is the first year of the government of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdez, which itself is called the government of change. This government brought with it high expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, there was no growth and even a decrease in the main indicators of economic development.
Low February temperatures have caused millions of losses in agriculture, limited the growth opportunities of the state economy, they are responsible for a decrease in economic activity by 3.6% in the first semester of this year. In the field of agriculture, there was a historical decline by 31.16%, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to the damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damage was recorded on 582,835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78.03% was completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% was found to be partial damage. The main crops destroyed include vegetables, corn and peas.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state increased by 68% and increased by 68%. From January to March, 55,053 residents of the state of Sinaloa were unemployed, which represents an unemployment rate of 4.53% with the economically active population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate in the state increased.
Less liquidity
