“We are witnessing rising unemployment, which is related to various factors. These include, among others, the loss of liquidity in the market due to resource constraints due to legislation approved by Congress in connection with the fight against money laundering. For people who illegally seize dollars, it is not easy to earn them, invest them or use them for something,” he said.
Stopping migration
L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Cervantes said that the demographic factor is also involved in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people leaving for work abroad, to the United States, has decreased, both because of the difficult entry and then because even when these people get abroad, it is difficult for them to get a job. So people stay and demand work from our state, and thus unemployment increases," he said.
Unreliability
The labour market analysis in Sinaloa is also deteriorating due to the growing unreliability that prevails in the area of working conditions. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the state's employed population works without paying social security benefits.
Other features of the labour market, such as low wages, are added to unemployment and unreliability. In this administrative area, the lowest salaries are from across the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was 5,352 pesetas by September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesetas.
