Debt
In connection with the economic downturn scenario, the government of this state asked the state Congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos. This would be earmarked for investment in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local Congress approved a loan of 2,600 million pesos. By November, no gains were recorded in the economy and no debt was recorded.
Reactions
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government, Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdés, pointed to the lack of management skills of the government.
Miguel Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, chairman of the National Chamber of Transformative Industries, said that in 2011 there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the government itself.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa was really small during this year. We have to work intensively to regain the land we lost this year. In 2012, we have to double our efforts, there was a lack of harmonisation of the efforts of all of us and, in particular, the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Let's hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Slowing down the economy
Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said that events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and limited its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frost. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to regain the dynamism that would allow to achieve an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. Therefore, at the end of the year we found ourselves well below the expected forecasts," he said.
Re-defining the mission
According to Theodore Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers’ Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed to more dynamic productive activities.
"Generally speaking, we observe that work is underway. We believe that a long-term plan should be prepared in which the goals and economic direction of the state would be redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resources Sinaloa has be mobilized," he said.
