Appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet tomorrow with the Italian president to introduce him to a new government that will face a crisis that holds the country over the abyss of economic disaster that has put the entire eurozone at risk.
The palace issued a report announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm he could form a government.
It is expected to represent a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," he told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that the obstacles were overcome.
"The framework is now well-marked," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, a much shorter time than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to fight the political and financial crisis, which has caused the amount of debt to rise to an unsustainable level.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve the tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore Italy's shattered credibility.
Due to the instability of the markets, interest on Italian BTP bonds with a 10-year maturity exceeded the 7% limit, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for bailouts.
