Quintet included the country in its tour on the occasion of the celebration of 20 years of existence
“The Costa Rican road is a dream that becomes a reality.”
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself assures that for them the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
This is what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil, said.
The group is on the South American continent as part of a tour to celebrate 20 years of existence and will be at a unique stop in Central America on Sunday, the 20th.
He will perform at the National Stadium at 7:30 p.m., alongside the angelic band The X and national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is an example of an interview whose full transcript can be found on La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n's website.
For your Costa Rican fans, this is a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
Traveling to Costa Rica is a dream that is becoming a reality.
In South and Central America, we are barely a second time and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation, it's a beautiful country, and I believe we'll be able to stay here for a few days.
So we're very happy to bring you our music.
I ask, because they literally adore the group here, fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your most loyal supporters?
Thank you for standing by us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people already talk about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have been done over the course of a few weeks.
We did some great shows in S<0xC3><0xA3>o Paulo and we hope to get in shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to this concert.
We love this country, we like to surf, we like the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves suitable for surfing?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. So we learned about Costa Rica through people who love surfing.
If we look at your tours, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we have no limits on what we can't do.
We will try to show the best show with various songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's wrong?
I think it’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs we’re going to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven’t played in a long time, we focus on them and we’re also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
This makes the show more interesting for us, and I think it's more interesting for people as well.
This tour celebrates 20 years of artistic career.
When you look back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, I'm sure you are.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we were going to be in one big rock band and that we were going to stay in it for more than 20 years.
We are aware of how much we have been given and we are touched that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are lucky to be able to look at the places we have always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group where the greats themselves are represented.
People from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
Surprisingly, when a movement emerges from a group of friends, it doesn’t happen very often.
From time to time, a group will form in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play with some.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stick together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a much longer time than the usual duration of the group.
I think, firstly, we are all lucky to be still in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are always interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends, and thanks to this, we have managed to open up musical paths that leave everyone enough freedom to experiment.
We believe in each other, we appreciate each other’s music, and I think it couldn’t have been better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew, it became increasingly easier to find balance.
We try not to go on tour too much, because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for music, you will remember that you have to respect music and what you gave it. You must not let yourself be carried away by being famous, rock stars. None of us ever really cared about this.
What do you think of Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote great songs and at first it was something great.
“We’ve been a band for three years and we never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating, because it took so long. The most important thing is that today we are still friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started working in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at photos, I remember Andy, how unbelievable he was, how I laughed at him.
She was an incredible person and we miss her very much.
The Las Robertas national band will be tasked with launching the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that that's why you chose them as pre-jumpers?
Yes, the production sent us videos with a few suggestions and we liked this group the most. That is why we are curious what Las Robertas will offer live and must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he's adding the first thing that comes to mind.
Who is influencing you as a bass player?
Lots of people.
The first to attack me are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all night about bassists that I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge even though it is no longer in fashion?
I think we've all always felt a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I say grunge, I think of the bands I mentioned like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the other bands that were born at the same time, and if music like that is still valid today, it's something great because it's music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney play better music today than ever before.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly gloomy character and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
That’s interesting because I feel like there are a few songs on the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very gloomy, although they may sound like a positive one.
For both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they're songs that are deeply dark.
I think that when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone from your family or a friend, these things will start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make bleak music.
Peru:
Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized at a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for muscle loss in his lower limbs, his doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving 25 years in prison for human rights abuses committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several illnesses, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated on four times and is now under medical control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Canal N that Fujimori would undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases within three days, where they should find out why it hurts and why it loses strength in the lower extremities.
Aguinaga said he believed Fujimori could receive a pardon for humanitarian reasons, but the former president himself did not want the pardon because he felt innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and added to these problems other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murderous squadron of troops operating illegally in the early years of his reign.
