There was an eviction of a house in which giant parties were held.
Aliens appropriated 11 of 13 apartments in a building in Balmes, 51
12 occupiers left the house yesterday at noon, not resisting
All indications are that the nightmare that the neighbors of number 51 in Balmes Street were experiencing is finally over.
Twelve people volunteered to leave a building they had illegally inhabited yesterday at noon, where they organized gigantic parties to wake up neighbors, leaving the building by court order without having to intervene with the police.
After the operation, the lock on the door was replaced to prevent a repeat of the situation.
"From now on, the entrance will be guarded," the administrator said.
The occupants, who took 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest are inhabited - took away all the electrical and partially water equipment, painted the walls and left behind all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
In the first three apartments, huge parties were held, which lasted up to two days and woke up the other tenants.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which was also damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that while the building was occupied, sales fell by 80%.
The owner of the disco emphasizes that the occupiers of the building made unfair competition for her, because they sold drinks for 3 euros, while the disco costs 10 euros.
In addition, the owner of the entertainment company had to respond to complaints from neighbors because of the noise, but the problems were not caused by the visitors of the disco, but by the residents of the occupied house and especially those who participated in the parties held here, whose frequency and intensity have increased in recent weeks, according to the angry residents of the neighborhood.
The owner of the discotheque explained that the problems were so great that they even agreed with the owner of the building and for nine months forgave her rent.
The city police also confirmed that they had received more complaints from neighbors about the situation in recent weeks.
The chairman of the city group of the People's Party of the PP in the city hall, Alberto Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez D<0xC3><0xAD>az, last week demanded that "the building be immediately evicted to end the problems of civil coexistence that the neighbors are suffering, and the destruction of the area".
The president explained that only one floor had been taken up before the summer, but in recent months the occupiers had reached all floors of the building and almost all apartments, and in one of them there had even been thefts.
In this regard, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to be consistent when it comes to acts against civil responsibility that occurred in the building".
Yesterday, the city police also cleared the building in Nou Barris.
At 3:30 p.m., police arrived at Building 35 on Mont-Ral Street after being summoned by neighbors who saw four people entering the building.
All four were immediately arrested.
The park or the mountains?
The architects met on the occasion of writing off a procedure that carries with it more than a polemic about the fees
The city’s 16-gate tender opens a debate on the role of Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the already extinct Corporaci<0xC3><0xB3>n Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this self-government printed several pamphlets in support of Collserola Park.
The leaflet defined the mountain as a large park of metropolitan Barcelona.
What’s more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York’s Central Park.
After the collapse of the CMB in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper limit of Barcelona, because the Catalan metropolis is one of the few that do not focus on the north-south axis, but up (mountain) - down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a nature park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with the savages instead of the Yogi bear.
That was the position until September, when the city hall announced a mega-competition consisting of 16 auditions for the same number of entrance gates to Collserola.
The gate, of course, records the idea of the park.
Either this, or someone's trying to put a gate on the field.
So the only question is: Collserola, a park or a mountain?
During the competition, both from the point of view of purely organizational and based on reflection about the city, this question becomes the central theme of all Barcelona architects.
It’s a topic as obliterated as when two members of this old caste, chosen to meet in the elevator, shake hands.
And it was this act that sparked one of the rare concurrences between what the three Barcelona architects and the preeminent university professors think.
Miguel Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the selection procedure is justified.
According to Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, after the issue of the Gulf side began, "it is necessary" to discuss the "mountain side", so Ildefonso Cerdo's speech on green apples was not brought to the end.
"We must proceed from the principle that the most extensive park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex," said the architect, for whom the name "gates to Collserola" carries a "lexicological trap": we should not imagine them "as entrances to the park, but rather as delimitation of zones where it is possible to act".
Modol, like Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n and Bayona with experience in the world of urbanism, qualifies the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" offering "some dangers".
The danger posed by the "uncertainty that the public place project presents today" after the experience of the 1980s, which in the Forum area had "his swan singing".
The first concern is the very definition of the boundaries where it should be built.
“To define something is to take the next step,” that is, in principle, to go one step further.
"It is necessary to keep in mind the new urban and planning tools, because the current ones (with reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause a real disaster."
If we focus on the question in more detail, Modol believes that the Collserola valley slope can be "considered as a park", but not the Barcelona part, for purely topographic reasons.
Modol also recalled that there is already work done by the Patronat de Collserola, which "should not end up in a garbage dump", although he welcomes the fact that the town hall offers his grémium, that it will intervene in the project from the "first moment".
Moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain and the city is a kind of pass that allows architects to get involved in the debate, but "does doubt" that it should be this technical profile that will lead the multidisciplinary teams ("it's all about skills," he adds) that need to be created: "Architects should only be tools."
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the title of this game is complex, because Collserola's global vision is missing in the tender documents: "There have been 16 tenders that address all the axis of the mountain - the sea, but there is no longitudinal study that would look at the area and understand it as a whole."
This causes that at least he, has signed up for all 16 tenders.
Otherwise, the design of a single gate may come across the concept and definition of the architect of the neighboring gate.
In his view, the city hall should guarantee that the zone immediately above Ronda de Dalt should provide a full-length zone of equipment that would ensure a smooth transition between the city and the greenery.
