Mexican Health Insurance Institute Starts Research on Gene That Causes Obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research in order to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the Institute of IPN
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to detect the gene causing obesity in children and young people. Research called "The genetics of obesity in children and adolescents" will allow to obtain results related to overweight.
In a report, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Biochemistry Research Medical Unit at the National Health Center’s Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team relies on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and from the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, with or without authorization, can also participate in the research. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in Valle de México, where they will conduct tests to young people every council from 8 am.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexico State) and since October 8, this activity has also been carried out at the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Center (East of the Mexican State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children have been obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics when it comes to the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors on Mexican children and young people and thus prevent the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the goal is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He specified that every Saturday, anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference) are performed on all participants, blood pressure is measured, the level of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin is determined, and genes are examined (trying to identify genes that are involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said the research reflects health care workers’ concerns about the alarming increase in child weight.
"Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was a 77% increase in obesity in boys and 47% in girls, and a dramatic increase in overweight," said the expert from IMSS.
He stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Native American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics is commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they get an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thereby determining whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-diabetes conditions.
So far, the information is confidential, and doctors give it to parents in writing and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent their children from getting sick.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, sitting all day in front of the TV and using vehicles instead of walking for short distances.
Excess weight is also caused by a large caloric intake, that is, greater consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins, and the genetic load that is the subject of this research.
There will be no asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers, creating a mixture that has better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature.
If the pavement was properly taken care of, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 pits after each period of rainfall in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, said Rafael Herrera Najera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, who also added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt pavements were adequate, it would be possible to remove them.
In his lecture The Technological Cause of Bursts, which he delivered as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership was developing modified asphalt with polymers, which should create a mixture having similar characteristics to asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, for example in some cities in the north of the country, to improve functionality and reduce the formation of pits.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a cluster of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules of high molecular weight called asphalts, and others of low molecular weight called maltens. Together they give asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt lies in the fact that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, said a specialist in chemical engineering.
A researcher from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Mexico City are covered with flexible tiles consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers is an asphalt insert, consisting of small stones poured into the asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that makes up the insert is flooded with asphalt.
During the passage of cars or when creating pressure, it is so possible that the forces in the tiles are well distributed.
If it were modified asphalt, it would decompose even better, according to the chemical engineer.
He added that on the asphalt insert the last layer, called a mantle, is placed, consisting of fine stones, i.e. sand also poured in asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the road.
Since as part of the pavement it will be exposed to a large load, the mantle must have a sufficient thickness and must pay attention to the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great impact on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is moist, the water spreads inward and it is difficult to get out, this causes softening of all layers of tiles and thus the formation of pits.
He explained that during the creation of pits, the film of the shell is first damaged and only then the asphalt insert is damaged. However, damage does not occur at one time, but it is a gradual process that should be stopped already at the first signs with the help of appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of pits, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of pavement must correspond to the load of vehicles and it must be ensured that this load does not exceed. Only in this way can we prevent frequent occurrence of pits.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that when it comes to asphalt, we still have a lot of work to do and research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow you to easily repair pits without having to use high temperatures.
