Since March last year, Japan’s economy has been paralyzed, now recovering from a devastating earthquake that has turned into a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster the country has had to face since World War II.
The first estimates by the Tokyo government put the material loss at $300,000 million, a wound that heals well despite a difficult global situation.
After three quarters of declines, the value of GDP between July and September reached such a position that it was possible to turn the page definitively: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% annually.
