The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is natural for an election meeting to be an opportunity to think about such deposits and the place that the energy from the core occupies.
The debate will be successful only if all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options are examined.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
There are 7 billion human beings on the planet so far, but demographic developments will cause electricity demand to double by 2050 if we do not want to rid a significant part of the world’s population of important parts of life.
At the same time, there will be a shortage of fossil resources to continue generating electricity, while not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a theme that is currently disappearing from environmental debates.
The Fukushima accident does not affect any of these parameters.
And that is why Germany is left alone in its decision to reject nuclear energy.
But this is not the case for Belgium, which subordinates its decision to find another source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which considers it right to build only last-generation power plants.
On the contrary, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to quote at least some countries, continue with determination in their projects.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its park by one unit by restoring the construction of a single power plant interrupted after the accident of the Three Mile Island power plant.
If the German model based on renewable energy is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts this.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the price of electricity, increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, a sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal power plants.
All these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves to be considered.
The European champion in wind power, which consumes 30% of its electricity, is also one of the biggest consumers of coal and gas due to wind irregularities, which is why CO2 emissions and Danish electricity prices are 65% and 50% higher than the European average, respectively.
On the contrary, thanks to the immutability of our energy policy, our neighbours will pay an electricity invoice 40% higher than the French households pay.
While in a globalised economy energy costs are a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industry on national territory, French businesses enjoy the benefits of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would cause a strong increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory beautiful statements about the re-industrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
The price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay, just as they fundamentally do not oppose this energy, as public opinion polls show.
Recall that the energy policy of our country has allowed to build a sector with 125,000 direct jobs and with 410,000 follow-up jobs.
The highly exportable sector brings to international markets a large number of small and medium-sized specialised enterprises creating jobs that cannot be transferred abroad.
If France decided to leave the core, it would sacrifice a considerable number of these small and medium-sized enterprises and lose 6 billion euros a year, which the country receives for the export of nuclear facilities and services.
Which power plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to run for 60 years while its manufacturer is scheduled to fail?
In solving the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no magical source for energy production, and that there is no devilish one.
The development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable energy facilities by the French industrial group AREVA demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is absolutely necessary to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have the State Office for Nuclear Safety, which conducts uncompromising and transparent supervision of existing nuclear power plants as well as the construction of a new plant in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, have the idea of safety in the blood.
In 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major accidents.
The only one in Three Mile Island occurred in normal operation and was left without human casualties and environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the drama was caused by the reactor concept and unforgivable human errors.
In the case of Fukushima, some seem to forget that the crash was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented proportions that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident in the same way as it did the previous two.
The fruit of this step and the cooperation between the French and German nuclear safety authorities, operators and designers is that an EPR reactor is a concept capable of resisting such phenomena.
While all interested parties who wish to build a nuclear power plant consider it, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be an excellent gift offered to the competitors of the AREVA Group and EDF and pave the way for them to take a leading position in nuclear development.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy solution for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and machinations dominate the debate so decisive for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity?
The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - the congestion of police, courts and administrations subjected to a policy of numbers, the compatibility of this policy with the status of a "human rights country" of which France boasts.
Recently, this was an administrative harassment aimed at foreign students, which became topical when the Minister of the Interior (see the Libération newspaper of May 23) declared that France "does not need foreign talents, bricklayers and waitresses".
But so far, it has rarely been discussed from the point of view of the economy.
It must be said that there is a fairly broad agreement between the left and the right in this area.
On the right, Jacques Chirac stated in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country where 2 million migrant workers are" and on the left, Michel Rocard, when he said in 1990 that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, fears of an invasion by hordes of Polish plumbers into French territory were shared to the right and to the left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden to the economy and French society.
The only difference lies in the degree of generosity that we are committed to providing to immigrants.
In his programme, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande confines himself to the banality of stating that joint developments will enable us to solve our “migration problem”.
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem may apply in elections, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in their recently published work Synthesizing the Latest Knowledge on Immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.): among specialists there is a broad consensus on the positive impact of migratory movements.
Restrictions on immigration are crippling growth and damaging jobs.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that these people can replace French workers, especially the less skilled, and create pressure to cut their wages.
But experience shows that, in fact, immigrants are much more a complement than substitutes for French workers by doing jobs in sectors with a shortage of employees.
Few skilled immigrants in sectors that do not attract French workers, and those most qualified in dynamic sectors where education is not enough to offer jobs.
Positive impact on wages
Just as the surgeon will have trouble working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, these additions between French and migrants cause the arrivals of immigrants to have a positive impact on the wages and employment of French workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration movements would trigger a long-term increase in real wages between 0.6 and 0.9%.
It does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems in European countries, on average, at 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that in Germany, an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will bring a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 to public budgets in his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy expressed a wish at the beginning of his mandate to come up with the missing percentage of growth "with prized teeth".
These teeth used to deter immigrants had the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a rare and fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, for although it was invented in Athens two thousand years ago, it experienced during the 20th century the tragedy of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the gulags, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, and colonels in Greece.
Some people may have believed that in order for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to make a choice and carry it out in the most direct way possible.
However, it is already known from Napoleon that it was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, though a necessary condition of democracy, is not sufficient and can become an “instrument of oppression,” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, organization of separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice.
The crisis of Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it has been the same since the beginning of the crises of politics and democracy.
Admitting the mistake of a Greek referendum of the type yes-no will have the value of a double revelation in this regard: a revelation of the necessity of a great return of political power, but also a revelation of a disturbing feeling of its impossibility, its inappropriateness.
This ambivalence must be thought out in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted today and that many of the Republican fighters are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We can get nothing if we demand a series of national referendums organised as necessary and disorganized.
Bianca exposed to the European absolutist monarch or jumping with his feet tied into the void of nationalist depths: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want guillotine knives, but a common, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - and we would no longer know where to stop the list - because the crisis is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe, bowing to the dictates of markets and credit rating agencies, suffering from its incompetence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is being humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is all of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty and with it every one of its peoples.
The management of the European project of democratic sovereignty must be restored urgently.
For only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, get rid of the government of the markets and prepare the future by investing.
The exit from the crisis will presuppose decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, otherwise it would lead us to disaster.
After a long struggle against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today is strongly demanding a European economic government.
Yes, sir.
But to think of it without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by citizens, would be a new folly and a new dead end.
We need to take on a new stage of European construction.
In order to form a republic in France, it was necessary to "be" republicans.
The interest revolution could not have been enough.
This lesson continues.
We need to build a Europe that is more economically integrated.
This can only be done by building a Europe of more politically democratic and genuine European democratic sovereignty.
Let us become Europeans in order to build Europe.
