Nord Stream, the new port of entry of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline directly connecting Eastern Europe to Russia and running along the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to work.
It has to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to properly celebrate this event.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part in the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea last Tuesday.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned the control valve of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will flow to Western Europe each year through the first pipeline with a length of 1,224 km connecting the region of St. Petersburg with the federal state of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline, which has to be completed at the end of 2012, will enable a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas to be supplied, which is equal to the total French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge building is a victory.
Poland and the Baltic states strongly opposed the project.
Nord Stream will actually allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being driven across the country by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing some power: the possibility of putting pressure on Russia by threatening to shut down its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet Pact", with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that it is a politically sensitive issue.
Western Europe, through its support for this Russian project, has gained greater confidence in its purchases.
But this is at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, because the project has created gaps between Europeans from the east and the west.
Russia barely managed five years ago to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western states with high gas consumption, whose deposits are coming to an end.
“This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us,” Fillon confirmed at the opening ceremony of the pipeline, demonstrating the point at which major gas contracts are a matter of both political and economic importance.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom’s leaders present in large numbers at Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with a concrete sheath to protect it from the anchors of seagoing vessels.
It rests at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, minefields from the Second World War had to be avoided.
“For security reasons, nearly a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers, which in its entire length is not interrupted either by valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was supposed to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were only reluctant to see Russian state-owned companies settle permanently off their coast.
“In the event of a malfunction, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute,” explains Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely to the builders, because the welds were designed so that the leakage occurred once every 100,000 years.
Control of the condition of the pipeline from the outside is carried out by an underwater robot pulled by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pressed with gas.
At the finish line, it will provide accurate information on any deformation of metal parts during the entire three days of the journey at 3 m/s.
The remote gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply secured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish line.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
The leading position remains Gazprom, which holds a share of 51%.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies set up a joint venture called Nord Stream in charge of the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased the company for five years with a renewable contract all of its gas transportation capacity.
“Gazprom will profit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported,” said Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, the investment costs have risen to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be reimbursed, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline exits the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the exit gate of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine - brand notebook
The Italian company Moleskine, which was founded 50 years ago, wants to bring back the joy of writing.
It brings the smell of adventure, the hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable with its black rectangular plates and its white leaves as if they have aged over time.
