Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, will then decide to launch a new design but distributed notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant working for the company, takes up the introduction of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique "moleskin" (skin imitation), which is used, for example, to adjust the surface of benches.
This type of notebook was highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought back to popularity an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand’s leader at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to settle at 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is far from secret production from the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were made.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to assemble an artificial portrait of the buyer, since the notebook will attract the businessman as well as the student or professionals.
The image of Moleskine’s notebook is that its owners are cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded.
The small Italian company, which initially had 12 employees, now has almost one hundred employees, and since 2008 has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He sends his notebooks to bookstores and, through the FNAC chain of stores, to small boutiques in the middle of cities where he was able to assert his identity.
“We have been following the spirit of the times and this need for new writing, through the tumultuous development of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of the Moleskine notebook: recently the brand opened the exhibition "Zach<0xC3><0xA1>zka", where architects or artists exhibit their notebook.
In August, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival, she also released new notebooks reminiscent of a leopard.
Moleskine benefits from its success and this cultural aura and diversifies its products: bags, diaries, pencils, laptop cases ... The brand extends to a wide range of carriers.
A success that aroused envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which is writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the number of unemployed disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
Today is the 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the entire population.
Is it depressing?
“No,” says <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, which organizes the Disabled Employment Week.
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable."
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times higher."
"However, there's still a lot to do."
It should be said that there are numerous obstacles for unemployed persons with disabilities before they go to work.
These are the elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low qualification: 80% do not have a baccalaureate, and of the 2.3 million university students, only 10,000 are handicapped.
And finally - long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work and represent the “core of the problem,” according to Christian Grapin, CEO of the Tremplin Association, which was founded in 1992 to help businesses accept disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
There are unspoken ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité Association found that the managers surveyed had a "weak level of knowledge about disabled people" with an "exaggerated idea of people in a wheelchair and mental or mental disabilities".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The last known figures, dating back to 2008, show a status equal to 2.6%.
“We’re now moving around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization charged with charging businesses that don’t comply with the law.
Proof is the number of 'penalised' enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which fell from 59,000 to 46,000 enterprises between 2007 and 2011 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, put a lot of pressure on businesses,” explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also demonstrates true awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
